06482nam a22010215i 9783110617276DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020947877  a97831106172767 a10.1515/97831106172762doi  a(DE-B1597)498950  a(OCoLC)1232282186  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aNA9348.E75bB45 2021 7aLAN0090002bisacsh1 aBellentani, Federico, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Meanings of the Built Environment :bA Semiotic and Geographical Approach to Monuments in the Post-Soviet Era /cFederico Bellentani. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XIII, 188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSemiotics, Communication and Cognition [SCC] ,x1867-0873 ;v2400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Infographics -- t1 Connecting semiotics and cultural geography: A new approach to the study of monuments and memorials -- tPart A: A Semiotic and geographical approach to monuments in transitional societies -- t2 Toward a semiotic and geographical approach to monuments -- t3 The multiple meanings of monuments in transitional societies: The case of Estonia -- t4 The cultural reinvention of monuments and memorials -- tPart B: The cultural reinvention of monuments in Estonia -- t5 Removing and relocating the Bronze Soldier of Tallinn as a translation strategy -- t6 Erecting new politically-charged memorials: The War of Independence Victory Column -- t7 The coexistence of old and new: The memorial landscape of Maarjamäe -- t8 Erecting new urban decorations: The Kissing Students of Tartu -- tConclusions: Towards a semiotics of post-Soviet monuments -- tList of references -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume analyses the interpretation of the built environment by connecting analytical frames developed in the fields of semiotics and geography. It focuses on specific components of the built environment: monuments and memorials, as it is easily recognisable that they are erected to promote specific meanings in the public space. The volume concentrates on monuments and memorials in post-Soviet countries in Eastern Europe, with a focus on Estonia. Elites in post-Soviet countries have often used monuments to shape meanings reflecting the needs of post-Soviet culture and society. However, individuals can interpret monuments in ways that are different from those envisioned by their designers. In Estonia, the relocation and removal of Soviet monuments and the erection of new ones has often created political divisions and resulted in civil disorder. This book examines the potential gap between the designers’ expectations and the users’ interpretations of monuments and memorials. The main argument is that connecting semiotics and geography can provide an innovative framework to understand how monuments convey meanings and how these are variously interpreted at societal levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCultural geographyzEstonia. 0aCultural geographyzFormer Soviet republics. 0aCultural geography. 0aMonumentszEstonia. 0aMonumentszFormer Soviet republics. 0aMonuments. 0aSemiotics and architecturezEstonia. 0aSemiotics and architecturezFormer Soviet republics. 0aSemiotics and architecture. 0aSemioticszEstonia. 0aSemiotics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Geography.  aMonuments and Memorials.  aPost-Soviet City.  aSemiotics of Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z9783110750